HEADWORD: Recipe
<hw>Rec"i*pe</hw> <pr>(r⟦ecr⟧s"⟦icr⟧*p⟦esl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Recipes</plw>
<pr>(r⟦ecr⟧s"⟦icr⟧*p⟦emac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., imperative of
<ets>recipere</ets> to take back, take in, receive. See
<er>Receive</er>.]</ety> <def>A formulary or prescription for making
some combination, mixture, or preparation of materials; a
receipt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a prescription for medicine.</def>
<mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a prescription for medicine.</def>
<mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a set of directions for preparing food from its
ingredients.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>a method or procedure for accomplishing a goal by
defined steps; -- implying a high probability of achieving the goal;
<as>as, a <ex>recipe</ex> for success</as>. Also used in a negative
sense, <as>as, a <ex>recipe</ex> for disaster</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recipiangle</ent>⟦br⟧
